<section xml:id="subsec-rotating-objects" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Rotating Objects</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        2.3 Rotation
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        <ul>
                            <li>Rotate an object given the centre and angle of rotation on a plane surface and the Cartesian plane</li>
                            <li>Determine the centre and angle of rotation given an object and its image</li>
                        </ul>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand the coordinate rules for rotating points about the origin through <m>90°</m>, <m>180°</m>, and <m>270°</m>, and that rotation preserves shape, size, and distance from the centre.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Apply the coordinate rules <m>(x,y) \rightarrow (-y,x)</m>, <m>(x,y) \rightarrow (-x,-y)</m>, and <m>(x,y) \rightarrow (y,-x)</m> to rotate points and shapes on the Cartesian plane.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Determine the angle and direction of rotation given an object and its image, and apply rotation to real-world contexts such as windmill blades and road signs.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>

    <introduction>
        <p>
            Rotation is a transformation that turns a figure about a fixed point.
            The fixed point is called the <term>centre of rotation</term>.
        </p>

        <p>
            During rotation:
            <ul>
                <li>The shape and size of the figure remain unchanged.</li>
                <li>The distance from the centre remains constant.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>

        <p>
            Rotations can be clockwise or anticlockwise and are measured in degrees.
        </p>
    </introduction>

    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>15 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>Students work in groups to discover the coordinate rules for rotation by physically rotating a triangle on graph paper and observing how the coordinates change.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>Distribute graph paper, rulers, protractors, and tracing paper. Circulate among groups and ask guiding questions: <q>What happened to the coordinates after <m>90°</m>?</q>, <q>Can you see a pattern?</q>, <q>What about <m>180°</m>?</q>, <q>Is the distance from the origin preserved?</q> If available, direct learners to the interactive tool to test their conjectures.</p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <statement>
            <p>
                <term>Work in groups:</term> Form groups of <m>2</m> or <m>3</m> students.
            </p>

            <p>
                <term>Materials:</term> Graph paper, ruler, protractor and tracing paper.
            </p>

            <p>
                <term>Instructions:</term>
            </p>

            <p>
                Draw triangle <m>ABC</m> with coordinates 
                <m>A(2,1), B(4,1), C(3,3)</m>.
            </p>

            <image width="45%">
                <latex-image label="triangle-rotation-base">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.7]
                        \draw[->] (-1,0) -- (6,0);
                        \draw[->] (0,-1) -- (0,6);
                        \draw[thick] (2,1)--(4,1)--(3,3)--cycle;
                        \node[below left] at (2,1) {$A$};
                        \node[below right] at (4,1) {$B$};
                        \node[above] at (3,3) {$C$};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
            </image>

            <ol marker="(a)">
                <li>Rotate the triangle <m>90^\circ</m> anticlockwise about the origin.</li>
                <li>Rotate the same triangle <m>180^\circ</m> about the origin.</li>
                <li>Measure the distance from the origin to one vertex before and after rotation. What do you observe?</li>
                <li>Compare original and image coordinates. Can you identify a pattern?</li>
            </ol>
        </statement>
    </activity>
    <figure xml:id="fig-rotating-objects-activity">
        <caption>Interactive Activity: Coordinate Rules for Rotation</caption>
        <interactive xml:id="interactive-rotating-objects-plane" platform="jsxgraph" width="100%" aspect="1:1" source="jsxgraph/rotating-objects-plane.js">
            <slate xml:id="jsxgraph-rotating-objects-plane" surface="jsxboard" aspect="1:1" />
            <instructions xml:id="inst-rotating-objects-activity">
                <p>
                    Use this interactive tool to discover the rules for rotating coordinates on a Cartesian plane.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <ul>
                        <li>
                            <strong>Change the Angle:</strong> Drag the slider at the bottom to rotate triangle ABC by 0°, 90°, 180°, or 270°.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <strong>Observe the Coordinates:</strong> Watch the text at the top left of the graph. It dynamically updates to show how the coordinates of vertices A, B, and C map to their new positions A', B', and C'.
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <strong>Test Your Own Shapes:</strong> Drag the vertices A, B, and C to create a new triangle and see if the coordinate rules you discovered still hold true!
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </instructions>
        </interactive>
    </figure>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>10 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>To formalize the coordinate rules for rotation about the origin and demonstrate their application through worked examples.</p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Scaffolding Strategies</title>
            <ul>
                <li><p>Connect student discoveries from the activity to the formal rules.</p></li>
                <li><p>Present each rule alongside a visual: <m>90°</m> anticlockwise <m>(x,y) \rightarrow (-y,x)</m>, <m>180°</m> <m>(x,y) \rightarrow (-x,-y)</m>, <m>270°</m> anticlockwise <m>(x,y) \rightarrow (y,-x)</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>Emphasize that <m>90°</m> clockwise is equivalent to <m>270°</m> anticlockwise.</p></li>
                <li><p>Walk through each worked example, asking students to predict the answer before revealing it.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <p>
            When doing a rotation:
            <ul>
                <li>Size and shape is preserved.</li>
                <li>Distance from the centre also remains constant.</li>
                <li>Orientation changes but not dimensions.</li>
            </ul>
        </p>

        <p>
            On the Cartesian plane, rotations about the origin follow these rules:
        </p>

        <p><term>90° anticlockwise:</term> <m>(x, y) \rightarrow (-y, x)</m></p>
        <p><term>90° clockwise:</term> <m>(x, y) \rightarrow (y, -x)</m></p>
        <p><term>180° rotation:</term> <m>(x, y) \rightarrow (-x, -y)</m></p>
        <p><term>270° anticlockwise:</term> <m>(x, y) \rightarrow (y, -x)</m></p>
    </insight>
        <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>15 minutes</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>To apply the coordinate rotation rules to rotate points and shapes, and to determine the angle of rotation given an object and its image.</p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>Work through the first exercise with learners step by step. Circulate during independent practice. Encourage students to identify the rule first, then apply it. For struggling learners, suggest sketching the points before and after rotation.</p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Rotate point <m>P(3,2)</m> through <m>90^\circ</m> anticlockwise about the origin.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Rule: <m>(x,y) \rightarrow (-y,x)</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>(3,2) \rightarrow (-2,3)</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Rotate triangle with vertices <m>A(1,2), B(3,2), C(2,4)</m> through <m>180^\circ</m> about the origin.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Rule: <m>(x,y) \rightarrow (-x,-y)</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>A'(-1,-2), B'(-3,-2), C'(-2,-4)</m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Point <m>Q(1,4)</m> is mapped to <m>Q'(-4,1)</m>. Determine the angle and direction of rotation.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Since <m>(x,y) \rightarrow (-y,x)</m>, the rotation is <m>90^\circ</m> anticlockwise about the origin.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

       <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Assessment</title>
        <p>
            <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p>
                    To formatively assess individual learner understanding.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p>
                    Learners independently complete a short assessment task (select from the exercises above or below).
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Collect and review the exit tickets to gauge learner understanding and identify any common misconceptions that need to be addressed in the next lesson.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
    </axiom>

    <xi:include href="../../resources-checkpoint.ptx" />
    <exercise  label="ex-25-2-performing-translations-and-rotations">
                <stack label="stk-25-2-performing-translations-and-rotations" source="stack/top/2-0-Measurement-Geometry/2-3-Rotation/2-3-2-Rotation-on-Different-Planes/25-2-Performing-translations-and-rotations.xml" />
            </exercise>

    <exercises>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Rotate point <m>A(5,-2)</m> through <m>90^\circ</m> clockwise about the origin.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>(5,-2) \rightarrow (-2,-5)</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Rotate quadrilateral <m>A(2,1), B(4,1), C(4,3), D(2,3)</m>* through <m>270^\circ</m> anticlockwise about the origin.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>A'(1,-2), B'(1,-4), C'(3,-4), D'(3,-2)</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A point <m>R(3,-1)</m> is mapped to <m>R'(-3,1)</m>. Determine the angle of rotation.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>180^\circ</m> about the origin.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A triangular logo is rotated <m>90^\circ</m> anticlockwise about a fixed point. State two properties that remain unchanged.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    i) Side lengths remain the same.
                </p>
                <p>
                    ii) Distance from the centre remains constant.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A windmill blade rotates <m>120^\circ</m> every second. Through how many degrees does it rotate in <m>5</m> seconds?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>600^\circ</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A point <m>P(x,y)</m> is rotated <m>180^\circ</m> about the origin. Write the coordinates of the image.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>(-x,-y)</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A triangular sign is rotated about a point and appears upside down. What angle of rotation has likely occurred?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>180^\circ</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A windmill blade has its tip at point <m>(3,1)</m> on a coordinate grid. The windmill rotates <m>90^\circ</m> anticlockwise about the origin.
                </p>
                <p>
                    (a) Find the new coordinates of the blade tip.
                </p>
                <p>
                    (b) Explain why the length of the blade does not change after rotation.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Rule for <m>90^\circ</m> anticlockwise:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>(x,y) \rightarrow (-y,x)</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>(3,1) \rightarrow (-1,3)</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    (b) Rotation preserves distance from the centre. The blade length remains constant because rotation is an isometry.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A square playground has vertices 
                    <m>A(1,1), B(4,1), C(4,4), D(1,4)</m>.
                    The playground design is rotated <m>180^\circ</m> about the origin in a digital plan.
                </p>
                <p>
                    (a) Determine the coordinates of the new vertices.  
                    (b) What happens to the orientation of the square after rotation?
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Rule for <m>180^\circ</m> rotation:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>(x,y) \rightarrow (-x,-y)</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>A'(-1,-1), B'(-4,-1), C'(-4,-4), D'(-1,-4)</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    (b) The square remains the same size and shape, 
                    but its position is reversed through the origin.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A triangular road sign with vertices 
                    <m>P(2,1), Q(3,3), R(1,3)</m> 
                    is rotated about the origin and maps to 
                    <m>P'(-1,2), Q'(-3,3), R'(-3,1)</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    (a) Determine the angle and direction of rotation.  
                    (b) State the coordinate rule used.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    Compare:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>(2,1) \rightarrow (-1,2)</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    This follows the rule:
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m>(x,y) \rightarrow (-y,x)</m>
                </p>
                <p>
                    (a) The rotation is <m>90^\circ</m> anticlockwise about the origin.  
                </p>
                <p>
                    (b) Rule: <m>(x,y) \rightarrow (-y,x)</m>.
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>


    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>

        <table>
            <title>Differentiation</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Scaffolding:</alert> Start with <m>180°</m> rotations only (negate both coordinates). Use tracing paper to physically rotate shapes. Provide a reference card with the three rotation rules. Colour-code the <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> coordinates to track how they swap and change sign. Pair with a stronger student for peer support.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>The core lesson activities as described above.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Extended Learning Experience:</alert> Rotate shapes about a centre other than the origin (translate, rotate, translate back). Explore composition of two rotations about the same centre. Investigate rotation matrices. Prove that <m>90°</m> clockwise is equivalent to <m>270°</m> anticlockwise algebraically.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-assessment.ptx" />
    <xi:include href="../../resources-reflection.ptx"/>
</section>